all-loving, compassionate Mother. Popular and scholarly interest in her has been on the rise in the West in recent years. Responding to this phenomenon, this volume focuses on the complexities involved in interpreting Kali in both her indigenous South Asian settings and her more recent Western incarnations. Using scriptural history, temple architecture, political violence, feminist and psychoanalytic criticism, autobiographical reflection, and the goddess's recent guises on the Internet, the contributors pose questions relevant to our understanding of Kali, as they illuminate the problems and promises inherent in every act of cross-cultural interpretation.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aKālī (Hindu deity). 4aGeneral. 4aHinduism. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Hinduism / General.2bisacsh1 aCaldwell, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDold, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFell McDermott, Rachel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGupta, Roxanne Kamayani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGupta, Sanjukta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHumes, Cynthia Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKinsley, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKripal, Jeffrey J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKripal, Jeffrey J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLawrence, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDermott, Rachel Fell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcNeal, Keith E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc